      ],
      "claim_key": "nvda.gross_margin_driver.fy2025",
      "claim_value": "higher_data_center_mix",
      "text": "NVIDIA gross margin rose to 75.0 percent from 72.7 percent, mainly because Data Center represented a larger revenue mix."
    },
    {
      "chunk_id": "nvda-supply-commitments",
      "document_id": "nvda-2025-10k",
      "section": "Note 12. Commitments and Contingencies",
      "page": 73,
      "locator": "purchase-obligations",
      "periods": [
        "2025-01-26"
      ],
      "text": "NVIDIA had 30.8 billion dollars of inventory purchase and long-term supply and capacity obligations, led by commitments for Blackwell introductions."
    },
    {
      "chunk_id": "nvda-inventory-risk",
      "document_id": "nvda-2025-10k",
      "section": "Item 7. Critical Accounting Estimates",
      "page": 38,
      "locator": "inventory-provisions",
      "periods": [
        "FY2025"
      ],
      "text": "Long manufacturing lead times and demand forecasts can create excess inventory or purchase commitments; fiscal 2025 inventory provisions had an unfavorable gross-margin effect."
    },
    {
